<div class="tool-seo">
  <h2>What is Base64?</h2>
  <p>Base64 is a binary-to-text encoding scheme that represents binary data using 64 printable ASCII characters (A-Z, a-z, 0-9, +, /). It's commonly used to encode data for transmission over media designed to deal with text, such as email (MIME) or embedding binary data in JSON, HTML, or CSS.</p>

  <h2>Common Uses</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Data URLs</strong> — Embed small images directly in HTML or CSS using <code>data:image/png;base64,...</code></li>
    <li><strong>API Authentication</strong> — HTTP Basic Auth uses Base64-encoded <code>username:password</code></li>
    <li><strong>Email Attachments</strong> — MIME encodes binary attachments in Base64</li>
    <li><strong>JWT Tokens</strong> — JSON Web Tokens use Base64URL encoding for header and payload</li>
    <li><strong>Config Files</strong> — Kubernetes secrets and other config systems store values as Base64</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Base64 vs Base64URL</h2>
  <p>Standard Base64 uses <code>+</code> and <code>/</code> characters, which are not URL-safe. Base64URL replaces them with <code>-</code> and <code>_</code> respectively, and omits padding <code>=</code>. JWT tokens use Base64URL encoding.</p>
</div>

